Anonymous Wed 19 Oct 2022 19:51:38 No.51747399 Report
Quoted By:
>>51746218
I’m admittedly not much of a writer anymore, but when I was, there were a few things that helped my out of a slump. If you’re struggling with actually writing, but you still want to be creative, I recommend trying other creative mediums for a bit, like drawing or coding. I don’t like forcing myself to write or draw, as that’ll make it feel more like a job than a hobby and it’ll eventually lead to me hating the process. But channeling that need to be creative into some other media has helped me feel creative while not forcing it, and eventually, I’ll get the mojo to write or draw again. It all just comes down to when you have that spark of energy. Something else that’s helped is to just watch a good movie or read a good book. I get lots of creative ideas from just those stuff, which made me want to write more.

The past perfect tense of 'have' is 'had had'. Me bad with words so I'll copy paste from Google.

>The past perfect refers to a time earlier than before now. It is used to make it clear that one event happened before another in the past.

"Had had" is the past perfect of "have". In this case, Jia is referencing two events. The fact Calloway had a daughter, and that something had happened to her. If it only read "he had a daughter" it would be simple past which would (I think? My proper English classes are long behind me) just be the past tense of have a daughter.
